[normal]              
[normal]Professor Wessely:[bold] The problem—not a problem, thank God—is that there are not that many suicides. There aren’t enough. There are these young Army men, but in the rest of the forces the numbers are too small to make any real conclusions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]Q33[bold] 
[normal]John Woodcock:[bold] Would that hold for the particular issue of people who we know have left the forces and have mental health conditions? How do they fare compared to people with mental health conditions in civilian life? Is that a level of granularity which is really too much?
[normal]              
[normal]Professor Wessely:[bold] The problem with that is we only know overall lifetime suicide rates beginning with the Gulf War in 1991, because until then, those data were not available and we know there that they are not elevated up until now. They have only just started collecting lifetime data for 
[normal]Iraq
[normal] and 
[normal]Afghanistan
[normal]—either this year or next year.
[normal]              
